00:02:25.020 --> 00:02:28.870
works when you're building
mobile web applications.

00:02:28.870 --> 00:02:32.000
So one of the first things I
want to talk about is the

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:35.760
network link conditioners and
really sort of understanding

00:02:35.760 --> 00:02:39.170
how you can better understand
and better test the

00:02:39.170 --> 00:02:43.630
experiences that you're getting,
when your users are

00:02:43.630 --> 00:02:47.820
experiencing their websites
on a mobile device.

00:02:47.820 --> 00:02:50.250
Because on a mobile device,
you can't always count on

00:02:50.250 --> 00:02:52.870
having a 3G connection.

00:02:52.870 --> 00:02:54.330
Sometimes it may be Edge.

00:02:54.330 --> 00:02:55.880
Sometimes, it may be Wi-Fi.

00:02:55.880 --> 00:02:59.770
Sometimes that Wi-Fi may be
worse than a 3G connection.

00:02:59.770 --> 00:03:01.850
Sometimes it may be
really spotty.

00:03:01.850 --> 00:03:03.810
Sometimes it may not
exist at all.

00:03:03.810 --> 00:03:07.120
So there are some great tools
that are available for testing

00:03:07.120 --> 00:03:09.050
on your mobile device.

00:03:09.050 --> 00:03:12.240
There's two that I think are
really interesting--

00:03:12.240 --> 00:03:14.230
Charles Proxy, which
is available there.

00:03:14.230 --> 00:03:17.250
It's available for the PC, for
the Mac, and for Linux.

00:03:17.250 --> 00:03:19.050
So you can install
it on whatever

00:03:19.050 --> 00:03:21.260
platform you're using.

00:03:21.260 --> 00:03:27.550
And it will go and basically
proxy all the network

00:03:27.550 --> 00:03:28.080
connections.

00:03:28.080 --> 00:03:30.500
So all the requests that
are going through go

00:03:30.500 --> 00:03:31.350
through that proxy.

00:03:31.350 --> 00:03:34.290
And you can specify how
you want it to behave.

00:03:34.290 --> 00:03:37.050
The other one that's pretty
interesting is the Network

00:03:37.050 --> 00:03:38.120
Link Conditioner.

00:03:38.120 --> 00:03:39.350
And this is a Mac tool.

00:03:39.350 --> 00:03:42.210
This is something that you need
to get through the Apple

00:03:42.210 --> 00:03:44.010
developer tools.

00:03:44.010 --> 00:03:46.620
So when you install Xcode,
you can get it there.

00:03:46.620 --> 00:03:49.740
And the Network Link Conditioner
is installed in

00:03:49.740 --> 00:03:52.400
your system settings.

00:03:52.400 --> 00:03:54.710
Let me bring it up here.

00:03:54.710 --> 00:03:58.950
So I'll bring up my tools,
my System Preferences.

00:03:58.950 --> 00:04:02.600
And down here at the bottom, you
can see this Network Link

00:04:02.600 --> 00:04:03.520
Conditioner.

00:04:03.520 --> 00:04:06.250
So when I start the Network
Link Conditioner, I have a

00:04:06.250 --> 00:04:08.450
couple of options that
I can choose from.

00:04:08.450 --> 00:04:10.460
I can choose the profile
and whether I want to

00:04:10.460 --> 00:04:11.940
turn it on or off.

00:04:11.940 --> 00:04:15.610
So first off, let's
go and turn it on.

00:04:15.610 --> 00:04:20.970
But let's turn it on for an
Edge Good Connectivity.

00:04:20.970 --> 00:04:23.020
So if I do this, you
can see a couple of

00:04:23.020 --> 00:04:24.390
things get set by default.

00:04:24.390 --> 00:04:28.750
It limits the bandwidth that my
device can connect to the

00:04:28.750 --> 00:04:29.730
network with.

00:04:29.730 --> 00:04:32.810
So I no longer have the full
network bandwidth available.

00:04:32.810 --> 00:04:39.130
I only have a 256K
kilobit stream.

00:04:39.130 --> 00:04:41.790
Also, I'm not going to
drop any packets.

00:04:41.790 --> 00:04:47.060
But it's going at 350
millisecond delay to all of my

00:04:47.060 --> 00:04:48.590
requests on the downlink.

00:04:48.590 --> 00:04:53.300
On the uplink, it's going to put
in 200K connection speed

00:04:53.300 --> 00:04:57.200
and a delay of about
370 milliseconds.

00:04:57.200 --> 00:05:00.390
So by turning that stuff on,
it's going to slow your

00:05:00.390 --> 00:05:02.320
network connection down.

00:05:02.320 --> 00:05:04.570
It's going to cause some
pretty slow things.

00:05:04.570 --> 00:05:07.120
So I'm going to bring up my
website because I know my

00:05:07.120 --> 00:05:12.310
website is probably not exactly
designed for a slow

00:05:12.310 --> 00:05:15.500
connection-- so petelepage.com.

00:05:15.500 --> 00:05:19.030
And you'll notice it takes
a little while for

00:05:19.030 --> 00:05:20.360
stuff to come in.

00:05:20.360 --> 00:05:21.940
And it takes that extra time.

00:05:21.940 --> 00:05:27.180
So basically, what it's doing
is pruning down my network.

00:05:27.180 --> 00:05:30.640
It's making my pipe smaller,
so to speak.

00:05:30.640 --> 00:05:34.200
So that way you can get a
better idea of how your

00:05:34.200 --> 00:05:36.600
network is going to behave
under low bandwidth

00:05:36.600 --> 00:05:37.270
connections.

00:05:37.270 --> 00:05:41.370
It's a really good way of
testing and understanding.

00:05:41.370 --> 00:05:42.770
Through here, you could
also go in.

00:05:42.770 --> 00:05:46.300
And you can set things like hey,
I want to see what a LASI

00:05:46.300 --> 00:05:47.330
network is going to look like.

00:05:47.330 --> 00:05:51.630
So notice here, we've got 1%
packet dropped and a 440

00:05:51.630 --> 00:05:53.780
millisecond delay.

00:05:53.780 --> 00:05:55.920
I guess it really helps
to turn this guy on.

00:05:55.920 --> 00:05:59.560
So I'm going to go ahead
and turn this on.

00:05:59.560 --> 00:06:03.190
I have to enter in
my password, so

00:06:03.190 --> 00:06:05.680
turn my password on.

00:06:05.680 --> 00:06:07.860
Let's just make sure I
got turned on here--

00:06:07.860 --> 00:06:08.990
on.

00:06:08.990 --> 00:06:12.100
So now, petelepage.com--

00:06:12.100 --> 00:06:13.890
I guess I didn't get
it on earlier.

00:06:13.890 --> 00:06:16.270
So now, let's see how long
this takes to load.

00:06:16.270 --> 00:06:20.490
Again, much slower, so
before, we saw it

00:06:20.490 --> 00:06:22.240
load reasonably fast.

00:06:22.240 --> 00:06:24.330
Now, we're still waiting
for content come down.

00:06:24.330 --> 00:06:26.350
We don't have that section
on the right.

00:06:26.350 --> 00:06:29.370
So I can see that the important
content on my

00:06:29.370 --> 00:06:31.530
personal website comes
up pretty quickly.

00:06:31.530 --> 00:06:35.460
The thing that I want people to
be able to see here, on the

00:06:35.460 --> 00:06:37.870
Thinking About, comes
up pretty quick.

00:06:37.870 --> 00:06:41.570
But the other content is going
to take a while to load.

00:06:41.570 --> 00:06:44.260
When the Network Conditioner
is running, you've got this

00:06:44.260 --> 00:06:47.340
little guy up here telling you,
hey, it's up and running.

00:06:47.340 --> 00:06:49.170
And so you can bring it up
really easily, if you

00:06:49.170 --> 00:06:49.960
want to change it.

00:06:49.960 --> 00:06:55.860
If you want to go and say, hey,
I'm on 3G or whatever,

00:06:55.860 --> 00:06:58.440
you can turn that on and off
pretty quickly-- really

00:06:58.440 --> 00:07:01.350
easily, without having to go
fight through lots of stuff.

00:07:01.350 --> 00:07:05.200
It's a good tool to be able
to use and understand.

00:07:05.200 --> 00:07:08.910
Charles Proxy is a really
powerful as well.

00:07:08.910 --> 00:07:11.370
Charles Proxy-- one of the great
things about it is it'll

00:07:11.370 --> 00:07:12.880
do all of your network
connections.

00:07:12.880 --> 00:07:15.600
And it gives you a lot more
inspection ability.

00:07:15.600 --> 00:07:18.010
So you can go in and see
what's going on with a

00:07:18.010 --> 00:07:18.920
particular request.

00:07:18.920 --> 00:07:21.870
You could take one specific
request and

00:07:21.870 --> 00:07:22.970
make it take forever.

00:07:22.970 --> 00:07:25.860
So you drop one specific
request, if you're doing a lot

00:07:25.860 --> 00:07:28.610
of XHR requests or something
to that effect.

00:07:28.610 --> 00:07:31.840
It's a good way to be able
to specify some of

00:07:31.840 --> 00:07:33.550
those things in there.

00:07:33.550 --> 00:07:36.220
On Android, if you want
to do this on a

00:07:36.220 --> 00:07:37.970
phone or on a tablet.

00:07:37.970 --> 00:07:41.780
You can do it on a phone
or tablet as well.

00:07:41.780 --> 00:07:44.640
On Android, you can set up
the proxy to go through a

00:07:44.640 --> 00:07:46.030
particular device.

00:07:46.030 --> 00:07:48.465
So it's kind of buried
in there.

00:07:48.465 --> 00:07:50.580
I'll get a blog post out or
something up on the Chrome

00:07:50.580 --> 00:07:53.450
developers page in the next day
or so, to talk about that.

00:07:53.450 --> 00:07:56.010
But you can go in, and you can
turn that proxy on, so that

00:07:56.010 --> 00:07:58.020
you can actually use that.

00:07:58.020 --> 00:08:05.040
Under iOS 6, if you have the
developer tools turned on, you

00:08:05.040 --> 00:08:08.200
can turn on the Network Link
Conditioner in there as well.

00:08:08.200 --> 00:08:12.250
So that you can see how the
network conditioner works on

00:08:12.250 --> 00:08:13.360
that particular device.

00:08:13.360 --> 00:08:16.950
You can test it, again, in
a specific scenario, to

00:08:16.950 --> 00:08:20.870
understand how things are going
to work, how they're

00:08:20.870 --> 00:08:22.930
going to behave.

00:08:22.930 --> 00:08:25.370
So let's go ahead and close
that and go back

00:08:25.370 --> 00:08:27.930
to our slides here.

00:08:27.930 --> 00:08:30.770
So faking it with the Network
Link Conditioner is just one

00:08:30.770 --> 00:08:37.730
way that you can understand how
your app is going to work

00:08:37.730 --> 00:08:40.700
for your users, who may not be
connecting with the same great

00:08:40.700 --> 00:08:44.600
bandwidth that you're
connecting with.

00:08:44.600 --> 00:08:47.470
One of the next things I want
to talk about is some of the

00:08:47.470 --> 00:08:49.460
developer tools within Chrome.

00:08:49.460 --> 00:08:53.460
Because Chrome offers a lot of
great tools to help you test

00:08:53.460 --> 00:08:55.530
your web application.

00:08:55.530 --> 00:09:00.530
And I call it faking it
because it provides an

00:09:00.530 --> 00:09:01.450
emulation experience.

00:09:01.450 --> 00:09:04.250
It's not going to be a true
experience because you're not

00:09:04.250 --> 00:09:07.020
running on the same hardware.

00:09:07.020 --> 00:09:11.610
The processor on my Chrome OS
machine or on my Mac or

00:09:11.610 --> 00:09:14.530
anything like that is obviously
much faster than it

00:09:14.530 --> 00:09:16.690
is on my phone or tablet.

00:09:16.690 --> 00:09:19.600
But at least I can be able
to go, understand

00:09:19.600 --> 00:09:20.670
what's going on.

00:09:20.670 --> 00:09:23.580
And I can get a pretty
good sense of how

00:09:23.580 --> 00:09:25.030
these things are working.

00:09:25.030 --> 00:09:27.290
So there's a couple of things
that you can do in the Chrome

00:09:27.290 --> 00:09:29.010
Developer Tools.

00:09:29.010 --> 00:09:30.880
So I'm going to bring up the
Chrome Developer Tools now, so

00:09:30.880 --> 00:09:32.230
that we can see what's
going on here.

00:09:32.230 --> 00:09:34.900
So I've got the developer
tools up.

00:09:34.900 --> 00:09:38.415
And I'm going to click on this
little guy here in the bottom,

00:09:38.415 --> 00:09:41.510
the little gears icon
for the settings.

00:09:41.510 --> 00:09:44.880
When I bring up the settings,
if I go to Overrides, I can

00:09:44.880 --> 00:09:48.430
change a number of
Chrome settings.

00:09:48.430 --> 00:09:50.530
So first off, I can change
my user agent.

00:09:50.530 --> 00:09:57.300
So I can fake out to my server
what browser I'm running as.

00:09:57.300 --> 00:10:03.210
So I could say, hey, I'm running
as an iPhone iOS 4.

00:10:03.210 --> 00:10:06.820
And so sure enough, it shows
here what my user agent is.

00:10:06.820 --> 00:10:08.280
You can see it showing
up there.

00:10:08.280 --> 00:10:11.410
But it also automatically turns
on the device metrics.

00:10:11.410 --> 00:10:13.430
Now this is one of those things
that I think is really

00:10:13.430 --> 00:10:16.860
powerful and really, really
useful to web developers.

00:10:16.860 --> 00:10:20.290
Because what it does is sets the
screen resolution to the

00:10:20.290 --> 00:10:23.920
same screen resolution
that I would get if

00:10:23.920 --> 00:10:25.000
I was on that device.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:28.340
So in this particular case,
it's got 640 by 960.

00:10:28.340 --> 00:10:33.150
So it's setting my screen
resolution to the right size.

00:10:33.150 --> 00:10:35.990
It turns on a font-scale factor,
whether it's going to

00:10:35.990 --> 00:10:38.730
scale my fonts or not.

00:10:38.730 --> 00:10:40.350
So you've got the
device metrics.

00:10:40.350 --> 00:10:42.580
So you can see what
your experience is

00:10:42.580 --> 00:10:43.750
going to look like--

00:10:43.750 --> 00:10:48.780
much easier to do this than it
is to resize your browser.

00:10:48.780 --> 00:10:50.760
I'm sure everybody has done it
here before, where you try and

00:10:50.760 --> 00:10:52.850
resize your browser down to
exactly the right size.

00:10:52.850 --> 00:10:55.230
And getting it to that
particular size you want is

00:10:55.230 --> 00:10:56.890
just a pain in the butt.

00:10:56.890 --> 00:11:00.730
So this is a good way to be able
to go in and say, hey, I

00:11:00.730 --> 00:11:02.320
need a particular screen size.

00:11:02.320 --> 00:11:04.830
So sure enough, there's
the screen size.

00:11:04.830 --> 00:11:08.780
You can see these things are
rendering as I expected it.

00:11:08.780 --> 00:11:12.645
One of the next things that you
can do is overriding the

00:11:12.645 --> 00:11:14.090
geolocation position.

00:11:14.090 --> 00:11:16.990
So you can fake out to the
browser where you are.

00:11:16.990 --> 00:11:19.910
If you want to say, hey
look, I'm in New York.

00:11:19.910 --> 00:11:20.740
Or I'm in Mountain View.

00:11:20.740 --> 00:11:22.320
Or I want to go test
something.

00:11:22.320 --> 00:11:25.860
You can go in, and you can
specify the latitude here and

00:11:25.860 --> 00:11:27.070
the longitude here.

00:11:27.070 --> 00:11:29.500
So that you can say, hey, this
is where I am right now.

00:11:29.500 --> 00:11:33.400
I want to just take my word for
it that this is where I

00:11:33.400 --> 00:11:38.730
am, in case you're doing any
kind of geolocation testing.

00:11:38.730 --> 00:11:42.810
And you can also say, in
particular, I want to emulate

00:11:42.810 --> 00:11:44.110
a particular position.

00:11:44.110 --> 00:11:48.400
So I want to say emulate
position unavailable, which

00:11:48.400 --> 00:11:51.550
may happen, maybe, if you're
in a nice cement room where

00:11:51.550 --> 00:11:52.910
you can get a location.

00:11:52.910 --> 00:11:57.930
Or maybe just the user chooses
not to provide a device

00:11:57.930 --> 00:12:02.600
location, going in and being
able to specify exactly the

00:12:02.600 --> 00:12:05.290
location or whether the location
is not available--

00:12:05.290 --> 00:12:07.240
another one.

00:12:07.240 --> 00:12:07.890
You can go in.

00:12:07.890 --> 00:12:11.760
And you could also do device
orientation, how the device is

00:12:11.760 --> 00:12:15.990
with the alpha, beta,
and gamma channel.

00:12:15.990 --> 00:12:19.580
And there's a great article up
on HTML5 Rocks, if you want to

00:12:19.580 --> 00:12:22.570
understand how those
guys work.

00:12:22.570 --> 00:12:29.030
One thing to keep in mind when
you think about that is all of

00:12:29.030 --> 00:12:30.960
the alpha, beta, gamma
is how you would

00:12:30.960 --> 00:12:32.230
normally hold the device.

00:12:32.230 --> 00:12:35.180
So in some cases, I'd hold
my device like this.

00:12:35.180 --> 00:12:37.050
But on a different device,
you might hold it like

00:12:37.050 --> 00:12:38.520
this or like this.

00:12:38.520 --> 00:12:41.520
So both of those are all things
that you need to take

00:12:41.520 --> 00:12:43.970
into account for the device
orientation and

00:12:43.970 --> 00:12:46.640
device motion stuff.

00:12:46.640 --> 00:12:50.110
Finally, on here, you can see
the Emulate Touch Events.

00:12:50.110 --> 00:12:53.220
So that's going to simulate
touch events and fire the

00:12:53.220 --> 00:12:58.400
touch events at the same,
when I click on things.

00:12:58.400 --> 00:12:59.930
So those are all available.

00:12:59.930 --> 00:13:04.460
I think Device Orientation
is available in beta.

00:13:04.460 --> 00:13:07.030
It's not available in the
stable channel yet.

00:13:07.030 --> 00:13:08.700
So if you need to go
in and check, you

00:13:08.700 --> 00:13:09.940
want try one of those.

00:13:09.940 --> 00:13:14.980
Go have a quick peek in the in
the beta or even in the Dev or

00:13:14.980 --> 00:13:17.320
Canary or even in the
Chromium Channel.

00:13:17.320 --> 00:13:19.370
There's a couple of new ones
that are coming soon.

